ds that Germany, France, and the United States are converging in their policies toward immigration control and integration. All three have adopted similar tactics and made similar institutional adjustments in their efforts to reconcile differences while tending national integrity.The author builds her observations into a model of ''negotiations of identities'' useful to a broad cross-section of social scientists and policy specialists. She extends her analysis to consider how the European Union and transnational networks affect identities still negotiated at the national level. The result is a forward-thinking book that illuminates immigration from a new angle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCitizenshipzFrance. 0aCitizenshipzGermany. 0aIdentity (Psychology)zFrance. 0aIdentity (Psychology)zGermany. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAffirmative action.  aAlgerian War.  aAmerican nationalism.  aAmericanism (heresy).  aAnti-Catholicism.  aAnti-racism.  aArticles of Confederation.  aCentrism.  aChristian Identity.  aCimade.  aCitizenship.  aCivil religion.  aCivil society.  aCommunitarianism.  aComparative politics.  aConstitutional patriotism.  aCultural diversity.  aDecolonization.  aDiplomacy.  aDistrust.  aEconomic reconstruction.  aEmancipation.  aEndogamy.  aErnest Renan.  aEthnic group.  aFederal Union.  aFrench Colonial.  aFrench nationality law.  aGastarbeiter.  aGerman Romanticism.  aGerman model.  aGermans.  aGood moral character.  aHippie.  aIdeology.  aImmigration law.  aImmigration to France.  aImmigration.  aInstitution.  aInternal migration.  aIslam.  aJean-Marie Le Pen.  aJoseph de Maistre.  aJournalese.  aKonrad Adenauer.  aKulturkampf.  aLe Figaro.  aLe Monde.  aL